Title: Directives Syntax
------------------------------------

# Directives syntax

A *directive* is a compact, uniform way to attach an HTML element — with an `id`,
classes, and arbitrary attributes — to a piece of your document, without dropping
out of Markdown into raw HTML. One small grammar covers three scales: an inline
fragment (a `span`), a single block-level element, and a *container* that wraps a
whole span of Markdown. The same `{#id .class key=value}` attribute syntax applies
at every scale, so once you have learned it for a `span` you already know it for a
`section`.

Directives are the workhorse of structural authoring in JMarkdown. They are what
you reach for when prose alone cannot say what you mean — when a paragraph needs a
class for styling, when a region needs to become a `section` or an `aside` element
for semantics, or when you want to wrap content in a custom web element you have
defined yourself. JMarkdown's directive support follows the `marked-directives`
convention but is extended here with a custom-tokenizer hook (see *Defining your
own directives*, below) that the upstream package does not provide.

This page covers the directive grammar itself. For the closely related
`@begin(name) … @end(name)` form — which solves the same "wrap a region" problem
but nests by *name* rather than by counting colons, and which can render to both
HTML and LaTeX from one definition — see [Block environments](block-environments.html).

## The three levels at a glance

Every directive begins with one, two, or three colons; the count selects the
*level*. After the colons comes a *name* (the HTML tag or custom-element name),
followed by an optional bracketed text and an optional braced attribute block.

| Level | Colons | Form | Produces |
|---|---|---|---|
| Inline | one | name, then `[text]` and `{attrs}` | an inline element (default tag `span`) on the current line |
| Block | two | name, then `[text]` and `{attrs}` | one block-level element (default tag `div`) |
| Container | three or more | name and `{attrs}`, then a closing fence | a block element wrapping everything up to the close |

The exact characters for each level are shown in fenced code blocks throughout this
page (and gathered in the *Reference* section). They are deliberately kept out of
running prose: the colon markers are live syntax, and writing them inline would
trip the parser.

The `name` may be any valid HTML tag (`span`, `section`, `aside`, `figure`, `mark`,
`time`, …) or any custom-element name you have defined (`my-card`, `exam-feedback`,
…). JMarkdown does not check the name against a whitelist; whatever you write
becomes the tag. That is deliberate — it is how directives reach custom elements.

## Inline directives

An inline directive, prefixed with a single colon, injects an inline element into
the middle of running text. Its bracketed text is its content (processed as
Markdown inline syntax), and its braced attribute block sets the `id`, classes, and
other attributes. The general form is:

```markdown
:name[text]{#id .class key=value}
```

The default tag is `span`, so the demo below produces three inline elements in one
sentence:

::::markdown-demo
A plain :span[span of text]{.highlight}, an :em[emphasized fragment], and a
:mark[highlighted note]{.warn} all live inside one sentence.
::::

The name can be any inline HTML element — `em`, `mark`, `time`, `abbr`, `cite`,
`code` — or a custom inline element. The content in brackets is itself Markdown, so
inline emphasis and math work inside it:

::::markdown-demo
:span[This has **bold**, *italics*, and math $E=mc^2$ inside it]{.callout}
::::

Because an inline directive is, at heart, just a way to emit an inline element, it
slots in wherever inline content is allowed — including as the body of a list item.
Used at the start of a list item, it replaces the item's generated marker with your
element while keeping the item in sequence:

::::markdown-demo
1. An ordinary item.
2. Another ordinary item.
:li[A styled item]{.red}
4. Numbering continues as written.
::::

## Block directives

A block directive, prefixed with two colons, emits a *single* block-level element.
The default tag is `div`. Its content comes from the optional bracketed text — and
this is the important part to understand, because it is easy to expect the wrong
thing.

A block directive **does not** swallow the lines that follow it. It consumes only
its own one-line form. The text after it remains an ordinary, separate paragraph:

::::markdown-demo
::aside[A self-contained aside, with its content in the brackets.]{.note}

This paragraph is **not** inside the aside — it is a normal paragraph that
happens to come next.
::::

If you want to wrap several paragraphs, a list, or any multi-line region, that is
a job for a *container* directive (next section), not a block directive. A block
directive is for inserting one element in one place.

A block directive with no bracketed text produces an *empty* element — which is
exactly what you want when the element is a placeholder you will populate later with
JavaScript, or a void element such as a horizontal rule:

::::markdown-demo
::ul{#dynamic-list .js-target}

::hr{.section-break}
::::

Inspect the rendered output of the first line and you will find an empty
`<ul id="dynamic-list" class="js-target">`, ready for a script to fill. The second
line shows a void element: JMarkdown knows the HTML void elements (`hr`, `br`,
`img`, `input`, `col`, …) and self-closes them rather than emitting a stray closing
tag.

> [!WARNING]
> The tag name `p` is a poor choice for a block directive. Because marked's own
> paragraph handling competes with it, a `p`-named block directive does not wrap
> its bracketed text the way other block tags do — the text leaks out as separate
> paragraphs. Reach for a `div` (the default) or a semantic block element such as
> `aside`, `section`, `figure`, or `blockquote` instead.

## Container directives

A container directive is the one you will use most. It opens with three colons, a
name, and an optional attribute block; it runs until a closing line of three
colons; and it wraps everything between the fences in the named element. The
general form is:

```markdown
:::name{#id .class key=value}
…any amount of Markdown…
:::
```

Unlike a block directive, a container processes its body as full Markdown —
paragraphs, lists, headings, math, even other directives all work inside it:

::::markdown-demo
:::section{#intro .goldenrod}
This whole region is wrapped in a section element with the given id and class.

1. A list inside the container.
2. Another item, with an inline directive: :span[styled]{.red}.

And some math: $\int_0^1 x^2\,dx = \tfrac{1}{3}$.
:::
::::

The closing fence must sit on a line by itself. Everything up to it — across as
many paragraphs and blocks as you like — becomes the container's content.

### Custom elements as containers

Because the name is used verbatim as the tag, a container is the natural way to
emit a custom web element that decorates or augments its content. When marking
exams, for instance, you might define a minimal `exam-feedback` element and write:

```markdown
:::exam-feedback
Your proof of Lemma 2 is correct, but the appeal to compactness in the
final step needs justification.
:::
```

The browser then runs whatever upgrade logic that element defines. Custom elements
also give downstream tools a stable hook: a region wrapped in `exam-feedback` can,
for example, be targeted by [Biblify](https://jmckalex.org/software/bibtex-in-webpages.html)
for a local bibliography.

JMarkdown places no requirement on the name's form here — `my-card`, `pull-quote`,
or `exam-feedback` are all emitted exactly as written. (This is unlike the
`@begin … @end` block environments, where an unhyphenated name becomes a `div` and
a hyphenated one becomes a custom element; container directives always use the
literal name.)

### Nesting containers

Containers nest, but because each level is delimited by a *count* of colons, an
inner container must use a **different** colon count from the one that encloses it —
otherwise the inner closing fence would be read as closing the outer container. The
convention is to give the outer container *more* colons. The example below uses four
colons for the outer container and three for the inner one:

```markdown
::::div{.outer}
Outer content.

:::aside{.inner}
Inner content, fully nested.
:::
::::
```

That source renders to:

::::::markdown-demo
::::div{.outer}
Outer content.

:::aside{.inner}
Inner content, fully nested.
:::
::::
::::::

JMarkdown registers container markers from three colons up to eight, so you have
room for deeply nested structures. This colon-counting is the one real friction
point of container directives: wrapping an existing block in a new outer container
means bumping the colon count of every level inside it. If that bookkeeping bothers
you, the name-delimited [Block environments](block-environments.html)
(`@begin … @end`) avoid it entirely — they nest by name with no counting.

## The attribute syntax

The braced block after a directive name is parsed by the `attributes-parser`
library — the same parser the block-environment attributes use. It accepts a
space-separated mix of shorthands and key/value pairs:

| Form | Meaning | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `#name` | sets the element's `id` | `#main-figure` |
| `.name` | adds a class (repeatable, and merged with any `class=`) | `.lead .muted` |
| `key=value` | a plain attribute | `role=note` |
| `key="value"` | a quoted attribute value (use this whenever the value is not a bare identifier or number) | `aria-label="More info"` |
| `key=42` | a numeric value | `data-count=42` |
| `key` | a boolean / shorthand attribute | `hidden` |

Shorthands and explicit attributes combine cleanly. Multiple class shorthands
accumulate, and they merge with an explicit `class="…"`:

::::markdown-demo
:span[merged classes]{#x .a .b key=value}
::::

Inspect that span and you will see `id="x"`, `class="a b"`, and `key="value"` — the
two class shorthands collapsed into a single `class` attribute.

> [!CAUTION]
> **Quote any value that is not a bare identifier or number.** The attribute parser
> treats characters such as `-` outside an identifier as token boundaries. An
> *unquoted* `datetime=2026-06-07` parses as `datetime="2026"` plus a spurious
> attribute, whereas `datetime="2026-06-07"` parses correctly. Dates, CSS values,
> URLs, anything with hyphens, slashes, colons, or spaces — wrap it in quotes.

## Reference

### Levels and markers

| Level | Open | Close | Default tag | Body |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Inline | one colon, name, `[text]`, `{attrs}` | — (self-contained) | `span` | the bracketed text, as inline Markdown |
| Block | two colons, name, `[text]`, `{attrs}` | — (self-contained) | `div` | the bracketed text, as inline Markdown; empty if none |
| Container | three or more colons, name, `{attrs}` | the same colon count on its own line | `div` | everything up to the closing fence, as full Markdown |

Container markers from three to eight colons are all registered, so containers can
nest by increasing the count.

### Built-in directives

JMarkdown ships several directives with fixed behaviour. The ones below are
documented in full on their own pages; they are listed here so you know they exist
and where the directive grammar already carries meaning. (Their colon markers are
described rather than written, to keep this prose parser-safe.)

| Directive | Level | Purpose | See |
|---|---|---|---|
| `today` | inline | inserts today's date | [Anchors](anchors.html) |
| `label` / `ref` | inline | cross-reference anchor and reference | [Anchors](anchors.html) |
| `TeX` | inline / container | raw LaTeX, emitted only in LaTeX output | [Sources & targets](sources-and-targets.html) |
| `HTML` | inline / container | content emitted only in HTML output | [Sources & targets](sources-and-targets.html) |
| `title` / `subtitle` / `author` / `institution` / `date` | block | title-block fields | [Metadata header](metadata-header.html) |
| `abstract` / `feedback` | container | styled prose containers | [Block environments](block-environments.html) |
| `comment` (and `Optionals`) | container | hidden-by-default regions | [Comments & optionals](comments-and-optionals.html) |
| `markdown-demo` | container | source-and-output side-by-side demos | [Demonstrating markdown](markdown-demo.html) |
| `game` | container | strategic-form game tables | [Strategic-form games](strategic-form-games.html) |
| `mermaid` / `tikz` | container | diagrams | [Mermaid](mermaid-diagrams.html), [TiKZ](tikz-diagrams.html) |

## Gotchas and edge cases

**Directives emit HTML even in LaTeX mode.** The generic directive renderer always
produces an HTML tag; it has no LaTeX branch. In LaTeX output, a `section` container
directive therefore leaks a literal `<section>` tag into the `.tex` file. This is
fine for HTML-only documents, but if you author for *both* targets, prefer the
[Block environments](block-environments.html) (`@begin … @end`) for structural
wrapping — a single environment definition renders correctly to both HTML and
LaTeX. The built-in `TeX` and `HTML` directives exist precisely to handle the format
split for content that genuinely differs between targets.

**Demonstrating a container directive inside a markdown-demo.** Because
`markdown-demo` is itself a container directive, a three-colon directive placed
directly inside a three-colon `markdown-demo` collides on the closing fence and
crashes the build. The fix is the same colon-counting rule as for any nesting: give
the demo a *higher* colon count than the directive you are showing. The container
demos on this page use a four-colon `markdown-demo` wrapping three-colon directives
for exactly this reason. When the inner example itself contains nested containers,
bump the demo's count further still.

**Use the `type=html` demo variant for raw HTML or scripts.** A `markdown-demo`
highlights its source as Markdown by default. When the example you are showing is
raw HTML or a script, add `{type=html}` to the demo's attribute block so the code
panel highlights it as HTML. See [Demonstrating markdown](markdown-demo.html).

**The closing fence wants its own line.** A container's closing colons must be alone
on their line. Trailing content on the same line, or a missing closer, will fold the
rest of the document into the container.

## Defining your own directives

For most authoring you will not need this — the generic grammar above already
reaches any tag and any custom element. But when you want a directive that does
real work (computes its content, parses its body specially, or emits a fixed HTML
structure), JMarkdown lets you register one. A directive definition is an object
with a `level`, a `marker`, a `label` (the name the directive matches), an optional
custom `tokenizer`, and a `renderer`. JMarkdown's `createDirectives()` factory adds
the custom-tokenizer hook that the upstream `marked-directives` package lacks; the
empty tokenizer is what lets the `TeX` container, for example, keep its body
verbatim instead of running Markdown over raw LaTeX.

The built-in definitions in `additional-directives.js` are the canonical models to
copy. To make your directives available to a document, point at a `.js` file from
the metadata header — `Load directives:` works exactly like `Load extensions:` —
or list it under `Directives` in a `.jmarkdown/config.json` for project- or
machine-wide availability. See [Extensions (complex)](extensions-complex.html) and
[Configuration files](configuration-files.html) for the loading mechanics, which
directives share.

